arXiv:2405.11409v1 Announce Type: cross Abstract: In 1982, Tuza conjectured that the size $	au(G)$ of a minimum set of edges that intersects every triangle of a graph $G$ is at most twice the size $
u(G)$ of a maximum set of edge-disjoint triangles of $G$. This conjecture was proved for several graph classes. In this paper, we present three results regarding Tuza's Conjecture for dense graphs. By using a probabilistic argument, Tuza proved its conjecture for graphs on $n$ vertices with minimum degree at least $ rac{7n}{8}$. We extend this technique to show that Tuza's conjecture is valid for split graphs with minimum degree at least $ rac{3n}{5}$; and that $	au(G) <  rac{28}{15}
u(G)$ for every tripartite graph with minimum degree more than $ rac{33n}{56}$. Finally, we show that $	au(G)\leq  rac{3}{2}
u(G)$ when $G$ is a complete 4-partite graph. Moreover, this bound is tight.
